\-	Creates a dash for lists
1\.	Number for lists
cd	Change directories
pwd	Print working directory
ls	Make a list of files in a directory
ls -l	view file permissions
#	Used for sections, one in front of a word makes it bolder/bigger
ls-F	Will show slashes to indicate if there are files
man ls	Manual for ls options
ls -lrth	Prints extra information about the files (who owns, who made)
cd ../	Step back one level in the directory hierarchy
cd $HOME	Return to home directory
cd ~	Shorthand for home directory
absolute path	Starts all the way back to the base or root of the computer vs a short cd (ex. /home/users/sen97/gen711-811/shell\_data)
ctrl+c	Get out of a loop if prior command had unclosed parentheses
head	Show first few lines of a file without opening the whole file
echo	Shows details about the variables you pin in (ex. $home)
history	Shows history of your code
grep	search through a file and return only the lines you are searching for
^	starts with
grep ^ (ex. grep '^c')	will search for the thing you are looking for at the beginning of a line.
>	Redirect the output to a file (ex. grep "^@" SRR097977.fastq > headerlines.txt). Saves output as headerlines.txt.
|	Pipe symbol, so connects one action to another
wc	word count, will print number of lines, words, and characters.
wc -l	word count, but specific to count the number of lines
ls | grep '^c'	pipe command to list things that start with "c"
ls *a*	List all files that contain the letter a
ls *o	List all files that end with the letter o
ls *[ac]*	List all files that contain the letter a or c
ls -laF	List who made the file
ls /usr/bin/	List files in bin
ls /usr/bin/*sh	List files in bin that start with sh
cat	print file to screen
less /	show the contents of the file
q	quit out of less
head -n; tail -n	shows the head or tail of a document; -n gives the number of lines you want
mkdir backup	makes a directory called backup
cp	Makes a copy of the file (ex. cp SRR098026.fastq SRR098026-backup.fastq) Second name is name of backup.
mv	move a file or folder
mv *backup.fastq backup/	move anything with the file name (ex. backup.fastq) to another folder (backup))
ls -a .hidden	List hidden files in the hidden directory
Permissions breakdown	rw-: r means you can read the file, w means you can write to it; and - means you don't have permission to carry out the code in that space (would be x if you can execute). st rwx = permissions for user, 2nd is permissions for group, 3rd is permission for others
chmod (-w)	change file permissions -w removes write of that user.
rm -Rf backup/	remove or delete a directory and everything in it
>>	appends something to a file rather then overwrite it
grep -v	Lets you omit things from a search
grep -B1 -A2 N SRR098026.fastq	Find N in the file and show one line before and two after.
grep -B1 -A2 N SRR098026.fastq| grep -v '^--',	Find N in the file and show one line before and two after, but exclude everything that has ^-- in it.

